abstract: While Senate Republicans tried to shake off the past 16 days as a bad dream, House conservatives praised Speaker John A. Boehner and blamed their more moderate colleagues for how it all ended.
snippet: While Senate Republicans tried to shake off the past 16 days as a bad dream, House conservatives praised Speaker John A. Boehner and blamed their more moderate colleagues for how it all ended.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Speaker John A. Boehner strolled into a late-afternoon meeting with House Republicans and gave them one key directive: go home after it was all over on Wednesday night and get some sleep. Their fight was done.

abstract: Senator Susan Collins, Republican of Maine, frustrated with the lack of progress on the government shutdown, put together a bipartisan group to move things along.
snippet: Senator Susan Collins, Republican of Maine, frustrated with the lack of progress on the government shutdown, put together a bipartisan group to move things along.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — As the government shutdown dragged on, Senator Susan Collins of Maine was spending another weekend on Capitol Hill, staring at C-Span on her Senate office television as one colleague after another came to the floor to rail about the shuttered government.

abstract: An impasse over the spending level for a stopgap measure to reopen the government was a stumbling block as Senators Harry Reid and Mitch McConnell spoke cordially but fruitlessly by phone.
snippet: An impasse over the spending level for a stopgap measure to reopen the government was a stumbling block as Senators Harry Reid and Mitch McConnell spoke cordially but fruitlessly by phone.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — With a possible default on government obligations just days away, Senate Democratic leaders — believing they have a political advantage in the continuing fiscal impasse — refused Sunday to sign on to any deal that reopens the government but locks in budget cuts for next year.

abstract: As the focus turns to the Senate to come to a deal on ending the government shutdown and raising the debt ceiling, senators from both sides of the aisle will join the Sunday shows to talk about whether they’re up to the task.
snippet: As the focus turns to the Senate to come to a deal on ending the government shutdown and raising the debt ceiling, senators from both sides of the aisle will join the Sunday shows to talk about whether they’re up to the task.
lead_paragraph: With fiscal negotiations between House Republicans and the Obama administration crumbling on Saturday, all eyes turned to the Senate just days before the United States faces the possibility of a devastating financial default on Thursday. Key senators from both parties will take to the political talk shows on Sunday to discuss the prospects for a deal.

abstract: Even though companies are likely to see sales growth under the Affordable Care Act, they have unleashed a torrent of lobbying dollars and stepped up political contributions.

abstract: The Times’s Eric Lipton wrote in March about new tactics employed by lobbyists in an effort to repeal the medical device tax.
snippet: The Times’s Eric Lipton wrote in March about new tactics employed by lobbyists in an effort to repeal the medical device tax.
lead_paragraph: The House voted in the early hours of Sunday to rescind a tax on medical devices that pays for a part of the health care law and delay the health care law by a year as conditions for financing government operations and avoiding a shutdown.

lead_paragraph: 8 P.M. (ABC) THE 65TH PRIMETIME EMMY AWARDS Neil Patrick Harris (rolling out the red carpet, above, flanked by two television executives) hosts this ceremony honoring the best in television, broadcast live from the Nokia Theater in Los Angeles. Michael Douglas and Matt Damon, who are nominated this year for their portrayal of Liberace and his lover Scott Thorson in HBO’s “Behind the Candelabra,” will present, along with the celebrity pairs Kerry Washington and Diahann Carroll; Tina Fey and Amy Poehler; Emily and Zooey Deschanel; and Allison Janney and Anna Faris. Other presenters include Jimmy Fallon, Tim Gunn and Jon Hamm. Elton John will perform in a tribute to Liberace. The “In Memoriam” segment will feature remembrances of James Gandolfini by Edie Falco; of Gary David Goldberg by Michael J. Fox; of Cory Monteith by Jane Lynch; of Jean Stapleton by Rob Reiner; and of Jonathan Winters by Robin Williams. Don Cheadle will honor television’s role in covering the assassination of President John F. Kennedy on Nov. 22, 1963, and the Beatles’ appearance on “The Ed Sullivan Show” on Feb. 9, 1964; Carrie Underwood will sing music from the era. Preceremony coverage begins at 5 on E!; an after-party special is at 11.

abstract: With a potential government shutdown looming, lawmakers including Senator Ted Cruz and Representative Nancy Pelosi join the Sunday shows. Also, the programs will focus on last week’s shooting at a naval office building in Washington.
snippet: With a potential government shutdown looming, lawmakers including Senator Ted Cruz and Representative Nancy Pelosi join the Sunday shows. Also, the programs will focus on last week’s shooting at a naval office building in Washington.
lead_paragraph: House Republicans set the stage Friday for a budgetary fight that could lead to a government shutdown, pushing through a plan that would defund President Obama’s health care law. Senate Democrats said they would not support it.

abstract: Democrats in Washington, in Texas and around the nation, marshaled by female activists, are clamoring for Wendy Davis to run for governor in 2014 -- no matter that her chances of winning are slim.
snippet: Democrats in Washington, in Texas and around the nation, marshaled by female activists, are clamoring for Wendy Davis to run for governor in 2014 -- no matter that her chances of winning are slim.
lead_paragraph: NEW YORK — Not since Sarah Palin’s splashy debut in U.S. politics in August 2008 has any female politician come out of obscurity and, virtually overnight, captured the eye of the political and media world like the belle from Fort Worth, Texas: Wendy Davis, the state senator whose marathon filibuster of a restrictive abortion bill is now history.
headline_main: Democrats Put Hope in Texas Star
headline_print_headline: Democrats Put Hope in Texas Star
